In the context of `PersistenceSubmodule`, `sSup` is defined as the direct sum. So `sSup D = ⊤` means the direct sum of the submodules in `D` is the entire module.

When we evaluate at `x`, we get `sSup p ∈ D, p x`. This is the direct sum of the submodules evaluated at `x`.

The key property is that `sSup` commutes with evaluation. So we can conclude `sSup p ∈ D, p x = ⊤`.

